beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Pours dark amber/brown with off-white minimal head. Aroma is of malty bread dough. Flavor is very sweet, yeast, lots of malt. Has hint of coriander and banana as well. Minimal aftertaste with awatery feel. A very good beer to go with good food, and have a bottle to store for later.

Straw yellow color, with white head that fizzes out. Yeasty smell with some light citrus hop notes. Tastes of some hop bitterness, floral hop notes, a bit of sweetness as well. Very lively in the mouth.  Palate is crisp and light, with a minmal dry aftertaste.

Bottle. Cloudy with big foamy light brown head that sticks around. Tiny particles, so small they are barely noticeable.  Aroma of citrusy hops, and molasses maltiness.  A bitter-sweet initial and finish flavor.  The alcohol is hidden in this beer until the aftertaste.  This is a very good, if powerful, beer.  Now is one of my favorite IPAs.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: On tap at CC : The smell is roasty with notes of cofee, and a bit of chocolate. Dark brown with a small beige head. The flavor starts with moderate roasted coffee with some very subtle chocolate and coriander.  Also, a bit sweet.  This medium bodied beer finishes with a coffee aftertaste.

Ive been drinking this for years now and never realized that I havent rated it. Pours a soft hazy orange with a nice thick frothy white head. Aroma is very very wheaty. Some citrus fruit and sweet fruit nectar. Flavor starts with a big grainy wheat kick with the big grainy flavor. Medium body and moderate carbonation. A definite refresher for the summer.

Cloudy copper/amber with no head. Aroma of raspberry, sweet malt and sulfur. Sweet taste of mild raspberry and grains.  No aftertaste, light-medium bodied, with a metallic finish as well.   Nice on a hot day,

Poured a nice browncolor with a thin off lite-brown head. Aroma was malt, a lot of toffee notes.  Flavor was more of the same. Heavy toffee caramel notes with a good malt taste and that fleeting of something else. A medium bodied beer with a chalky finish.  An interesting beer.

Dark amber/brown with off-white head. Strange fruity esters up front, before the malt smell over. Has a caramel flavor with smokey taste taking over through the middle and finish. A dry finish, not my favorite.
beer_name: Big Rock Chop House Stoney Strong Scotch Ale

review_blob: A ruby-amber pour with some small white-head and decent lacing.  A nice caramel toffee smell.  Had a slick feel to this medium bodied beer.  Slightly sweet with its roasted malts tasting, and I found a bit of smokeyness as well.  A good beer.

Pours a brown so dark it is nearly black. Medium off white head which quickly dissipates. Strong aroma of caramel malts with coffee and chocolate notes.  Also has a smokey smell to it as well.  Tastes like toasted coffee and a hint of chocolate with a sweet finish. A delicious beer.

Draft. Pours a hazy light amber color with a medium sized off white head. The aroma was a burst of fresh citrusy hops, grapefruit, pine, and some sweet malt. The flavor is more fresh citrus hops, grapefruit, moderately sweet malt, herbal, pine, heavy dry bitter finish. The bitterness lingers for a while. Medium bodied, rough at the start, but very enjoyable.

Amber/brown color, fizzy tan head, mild lacing. Aroma of roasty malt / molasses. Flavor is chocolate and roasty malt. The chocolate is not overly sweet. There is a minor bitterness in the flavor. Medium bodied with a sryupy, dry finish. A good one, or two, or three...

Pours a clear copper/brown color with a medium head. Good head retention and lacing. Aroma of sweet malts, grain, caramel and hops with a bit of a pine note. Taste is toasted malts with sweet-like fruit notes and grassy hops. Light-to-medium bodied.   Smooth, and very easy to drink.
UPDATED: MAY 27, 2009

Bottle. Pleasant citrus and pine aroma with mild caramel and toast background. Clear amber-ruby with lots of carbonation up to a lasting, thick white head. Very balanced with a strong malt presence and well-rounded hop character providing both bitterness and a mild pine and orange peel flavor. Very full-bodied.
UPDATED: MAY 4, 2009
beer_name: Dragonmead Under the Kilt Wee Heavy

review_blob: A copper / amber appearance, some lacing that sticks and a lasting head. Tons of hops which are a little overpowering.  Smells of citrus and pine from the hops, but still has some sweet/malt smell as well. The flavor is a little more balanced than the smell. Not too heavy, good mouthfeel and an enjoyable hoppy-bitter finish/aftertaste.

Bottle, a dark amber/brown with a quickly dissipating, tan head. The smell is mostly malt and sweet caramel, with hints of nut and raisin. A very well balanced, complex beer, with an average length finish.  Larry Bell made no effort to hide the alcohol profile in this one, making it fairly robust, with a very mild hop finish.

2009 bottle. Poured a dark amber color with a nice fluffy head. This beer had very good lacing. Malty smell and also sweet fruit and a hint of spice (pepper). A sweet caramel malt taste with a nice balance of citrus hops. Loved the slightly bitter finish. Thought this was much better than the Dead Guy.

Bottle. Great beige color head that was quite rocky and long lasting, with a hazy brownish purple body. Molasses  and brown sugar aroma with notes of yeast, raisins, and bready notes. Creamy mouthfeel and tastes of sweet caramel, and a bit of cherry with just a hint of alcohol in the finish. Great beer.

Pours a bright, clear gold with a small amount of near-white head. Aroma has a bit of grain and dough to it, but definately a pine scent.  Spicy/sweet flavor contains the elements of the aroma with a little bitter finish. Medium body. Soft. Easy to drink. Great!
beer_name: New Holland Black Tulip Trippel Ale

review_blob: Poured velvety black with a thick snowy chocolate head with sensuous lacing. Aroma is nutty, caramel, chocolate, maple, vanilla, brown sugar, port. Flavor is ridiculously chocolate malty, some roasted barley, caramel, toffee, vanilla, and coffee. The carbonation is slightl but does accentuate the oak finish. Otherwise the palate is velvet but not thick.  One of my all time favorites!

A great example of what an Imperial IPA should taste like. Aroma is strong with hops with notes of citrus, pine, and grass.  The Carbonation level is perfect. This beer has a strong bitter finish, the alchol is not very noticable, despite the 10%. An awesome IPA for any hophead!

It pours a hazy golden color. A frothy white head.  The aroma of the hops is evident from the beginning, I can smell a little pine in it as well. It has a nice sweet hoppy taste with a tart-bitter finish. It is a very flavorable IPA.

Deep/dark  brown pour, mocha almost purple head.  Roasted everything, yet balanced well by a creamy sweetness, with vanilla sugary quality, good with the spent coffe ground notes and light bittering finish.

Pours a deep ruby- almost pitch black with a fantastic two-finger, creamy, tan head that lasts throughout.  Aromas of roasted malt, milk chocolate, raisins. Taste is medium bodied with some spicy hops and cocoa . Finish adds a nice touch of bittering hops. Oily mouthfeel. Aftertaste is muted hops with some milk chocolate.
A clear yellow/gold lager pour. Sweet citrus/pine aromas. Grainy malt flavors with a minimal hops and a bit of spice to it.  Very clean finishing, a bit astringent.

Had on tap at John Cowleys in Farmington, supposedly the first time its been served outside of the Eccentric Cafe!  A ligh/cloudy/yellow appearance with a creamy white head to it.  No overpowering smell to it, a good balance.  Has a sweet taste to it, with a slight hint of hops & bitterness to it as well.  A lite to medium bodied ale, with minimal aftertaste.  A decent everyday beer....
Smells and tastes like a malty dough with yeast. Appears a cloudy golden  with white head.  Good balanced flavor with malts & hops.  A short chalky aftertaste.

12 oz bottle. Cloudy orange body, thick, puffy buff head. Spicy nose with bitter pine and citrus brightness. Citrus and pine taste, backed by toasty malts. Dense flavor profile and crisp, biting mouthfeel.  Average aftertaste for an IPA with a slight metallic finish.
Thin brown head held with some carbonation behind it. A black beer. Huge dusty aroma like breathing coffee dust with a bit of raisins. A very strong alcholic taste.

An amber color brew with some off white head. Decent lacing. Light dough / grain aroma. An acidic feel in the mouth, results with a dry-bitter finish.  Unlike some of the double IPAs, Arcadia kept the alcohol level under 10% and thus this big brew is not only excellent, but also very drinkable.

Body is ruby color with only a little bit of off white head around the outside of the glass. Aroma is fully of cherries, wood, and vinegar. Very carbonated feeling on the front end, but the bubbles are quickly dissipating. The flavor is pretty sour with a bit of a red wine vinegar taste, then has a little metallic chalky finish.

This poured hazy and light golden in color with a white head that faded gradually. The aromas were of lemon rind, grapefruit, pine and some spice. In the mouth it is light-bodied with lots of carbonation and tartness. The finish turns dry and maintains the bitter tartness from the front of the palate.

Nice citrus flesh aroma. Good spice/ floral character, with a bit of banana to it. Pours a clearish bright gold, with a rim of white.  Tastes a little dry & tart. Fresh and light. Malts are a bit light and eaten up, has taste of champagne to it, but the spiced character works well. The minerals back up the spice. Excellent medium bodied saison.
beer_name: Big Rock Chop House Saison St. Clair

review_blob: Color is a very hazy golden with off white head fades into a barely hairline lacing. Aroma is sour and a bit of vinegar, kind of a thick, malty sourness. Taste is lightly acidic with a lemon, non-citric, thick sourness. Its nice, easy drinking, yet medium to full bodied.
beer_name: Big Rock Chop House Reserve Farmhouse Ale

review_blob: Pours light golden with fluffy white head. Some sour fruit tingle your nostrils, plus there is also a slight mustiness and a bit of banana thrown the mix. Tasty beer that is sour, some spicy sweetness but definately has a sour edge.  A medium bodied beer with a oily feel to it.

Pours copper with a nice, light brown head. Aroma shows raspberry, balsamic vinegar and oak. Palate has sweet malt that brings berries before the oak kicks into gear and delivers a dry, salty mustiness to it. Finishes with chalky, slightly tart acidity.

Aroma is funky, grapefruit, cider and a touch of spice. Flavor starts off with some sour grapes and grapefruit and has a salty finish. Spice from the yeast shows up as well. The thin palate is tart and dry.  Not my style, nor my favorite.

The beer is moderately malty with a light bread aroma. The beer also smells a bit like hay mixed with some citrus fruit juice, mainly lemon. It pours with an average white head that is white in color. The initial flavor is moderately sweet and finishes sour. It is light according to the palate with a dry texture and the carbonation is fizzy. The finish feel of this beer is a little watery.

A very well done tripel, growler from Dragonmead itself. Aroma was huge. Strong yeast and light pine/fruit with bit of honey. Pour was a cloudy hazy gold, white head and a hint of sediment floating around. Taste was great. Strong apple, pear and fruit cocktail with a yeasty acidic aftertaste. Nice carbonation and pretty easy to drink for 10%.
beer_name: Dragonmead Final Absolution Belgian Style Trippel

review_blob: Pours a cloudy ruby color with a good amount of off whitehead. Aroma has malty, hints of citrus, belgian yeasts and spices, and bit of alcohol smell. Flavor is sweet in the beginning, turning slightly acid near the end. A bit of carbonation with tiny bubbles tingle giving this a nice mouthfeel. Decent quad, a little harsh but I still enjoyed this one.

Pale golden color, white head. Aroma of hops and malts, some clove spices and yeast. Flavor is very malty, but nicely balanced by the hoppy bitterness and a slightly yeasty taste. Very smooth palate, soft and creamy mouthfeel with a medium texture. A nice balanced beer.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Dark, clear ruby color with a foamy off white head. Slight metallic aroma with hints of malt and grains. Strong roasted malt flavors with a slightly bitter finish and a minimal aftertaste . Medium bodied and finishes a little chalky and very smooth. Very enjoyable beer, but not the best.

Not my first time tasting.  Really good lager, and most people are willing to drink it. Pour is a nice deep amber, with a nice mild hoppiness in the nose. Good head and lacing on this beer. Taste is crisp. Initially is slightly hoppy/sweet , then finishes a little bitter, and well balanced with the malt. Very good.

Poured a very light straw color with a very small white head.  Really liked the way it looked in the pint glass.  Smelled alright, earthy, and sweet flowery malt. First sip was allright, but as I went on, it was apparent that you could not drink too many of these. Taste was a little acidic in the beginning, then finished with a lot of banana flavors which remained with th
Amber-brown,light sediment haze,small beige head. Small malt/brown sugar alcohol smell.  Overly sweet brown sugar malt profile, almost like syrup.  Medium alcholol heat,softly carbonated.

Very nice beer, pours dark brown, medium thickness on the palate, a little like syrup - not over done, licorice, hint of pepper, like raisins. The smell is nice, similar to rootbeer, mild burn hides the alcohol and a chaulky finish..
Medium reddish color with an off white head. Fruity-cherries abound in the aroma. Slightly sweet, tart and syrupyat once. Alcohol burn at the end of the swallow.

Copper red body with a dense white head. Aroma has a warming alcohol feeling . Also some hint of fruit in the background here. Flavor is sweet malt, candy sugar, citrus and herbs. A full bodied beer with a complex taste of Christmas.
